<td id="title_text"><h1><a title="Break" class="currentChild" href="Break">Break</a></h1></td>



</tr></table>
</td>
</tr></table></div>



<div id="content" class="content wikipage" lang="en" dir="ltr">
<p id="l1">
In <a title="Screen Printing" href="Screen_Printing">screen printing</a>, the release of the screen fabric from the <a title="Substrate" href="Substrate">substrate</a> at the end of a printing stroke. 
</p>
<p id="l3">
Also in <a title="Screen Printing" href="Screen_Printing">screen printing</a>, <em>break</em> refers to a tear in the screen fabric or the <a title="Stencil" href="Stencil">stencil</a> due to mechanical stress. 
</p>
<p id="l5">
<em>Break</em> also refers to a tear or complete severing of a <a title="Web" href="Web">web</a> of <a title="Substrate" href="Substrate">substrate</a>. See <a title="Web Break" href="Web_Break">Web Break</a>. 
</p>
<p id="l7">
In printing ink, <em>break</em> refers to the separation of a <a title="Resin" href="Resin">resin</a> from the rest of the <a title="Varnish" href="Varnish">varnish</a>. 
</p>
<p id="l9">
In networking, the term <em>break</em> refers to any interruption of data transmission. 
</p>
